snippet.textDisplay:
Jazza, I'd love to see you perhaps maul the pigment powder, into the alcohol, in a mortar and pestle. If at all possible in the future. See if that gives you a smoother result and consistent coverage!

This idea came to me because of you saying how the pigment was separating from the alcohol. When watercolor is made from scratch (pigment powder), you have to maul the pigment into the binder on a flat slab for 30-60+ mins to get a smooth result. With you using alcohol, however that's why I recommended the mortar and pestle. The binder used in watercolor making is thicker and doesn't run off the slab as easily. Of course your alcohol is much thinner so that's going to run off the flat surface instantly. I'm not sure if mauling the powder in the mortar and pestle with alcohol would work honestly, but it will be interesting to see! You could then fill the watercolor pens again or maybe just use a normal paint brush. Don't use that mortar and pestle for food again lol.

Honestly, I'd love to see you make watercolor paints too from scratch! The people here on YouTube I've seen make good videos are Arleebean and Penholder Art. As for the binder you can make your own from scratch with the recipes found online or buy some already made! I'm not entirely sure what you would do with the supplies after trying it out, but it would be a fun (but messy) experience and maybe if you like it enough you could continue to make your own in the future :)

Best wishes to you and your family and thanks for reading this long comment xD
